oduces cytotrophoblasts","Cytotrophoblasts develop from differentiated syncytiotrophoblast","Cytotrophoblasts and syncytiotrophoblast develop independently"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecytotrophoblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are mononuclear cells that comprise the inner layer of the trophoblast. These cells actively divide and \u003Cstrong\u003Efuse together to form\u003C/strong\u003E the outer \u003Cstrong\u003Esyncytiotrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E layer, which is a continuous multinucleated mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe syncytiotrophoblast is responsible for hormone production (particularly human chorionic gonadotropin) and maternal-fetal exchange. Both layers are essential for successful implantation and early placental development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cytotrophoblasts are the inner layer of trophoblast cells that fuse to form the syncytiotrophoblast","Syncytiotrophoblast is a multinucleated layer that produces human chorionic gonadotropin","Both trophoblast layers are essential for early placental development and implantation"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48280"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15841"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48280"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-18T21:22:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-18T21:23:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8532"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62830"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat